#: src/platform_support.md:1
msgid "Platform Support"
msgstr "平臺支援"

#: src/platform_support.md:3
msgid ""
"Being built on cargo and rustc, maturin is limited by [rust's platform "
"support](https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/rustc/platform-support.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:5
msgid "Automated tests"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:7
msgid ""
"On GitHub actions, windows, macOS and linux are tested, all on 64-bit x86. "
"FreeBSD is also tested though Cirrus CI, but might get removed at some "
"point. Since CI is very time intensive to maintain, I'd like to stick to "
"GitHub action and these three platforms."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:12
msgid "Releases"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:14
msgid "The following targets are built into wheels and downloadable binaries:"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:16
msgid "Windows: 32-bit and 64-bit x86 as well as arm64"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:17
msgid ""
"Linux: x86, x86_64, armv7, aarch64 and ppc64le (musl), as well as s390x (gnu)"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:18
msgid "macOS: x86_64 and aarch64"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:20
msgid "Other Operating Systems"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:22
msgid ""
"It should be possible to build maturin and for maturin to build wheels on "
"other platforms supported by rust. To add a new os, add it in target.rs and, "
"if it doesn't behave like the other unixes, in `PythonInterpreter::get_tag`. "
"Please also submit the output of `python -m sysconfig` as a file in the "
"`sysconfig` folder. It's ok to edit setup.py to deactivate default features "
"so `pip install` works, but new platforms should not require complex "
"workaround in `compile.rs`."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:28
msgid "Architectures"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:30
msgid ""
"All architectures included in manylinux (aarch64, armv7l, ppc64le, ppc64, "
"i686, x86_64, s390x) are supported. I'm not sure whether it makes sense to "
"allow architectures that aren't even supported by [manylinux](https://github."
"com/pypa/manylinux)."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:34
msgid "Python Support"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:36
msgid ""
"CPython 3.8 to 3.14 are supported and tested on CI, though the entire 3.x "
"series should work. This will be changed as new python versions are released "
"and others have their end of life."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:39
msgid "PyPy 3.8 and later also works, as does GraalPy 23.0 and later."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:41
msgid "Manylinux/Musllinux"
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:43
msgid ""
"`manylinux2014` and  its newer versions as well as `musllinux_1_1` and its "
"newer versions are supported."
msgstr ""

#: src/platform_support.md:46
msgid ""
"Since Rust and the manylinux project drop support for old manylinux/"
"musllinux versions sometimes, after maturin 1.0 manylinux version bumps will "
"be minor versions rather than major versions."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:1
msgid "Distribution"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:3
msgid "Build Wheels"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:5
msgid ""
"When building Rust binary or library, it's possible to depend on libraries "
"and symbols only available on the build machine. To ensure the wheels are "
"portable, native python modules on linux must only dynamically link a set of "
"libraries and symbols called manylinux and musllinux. The pypa offers "
"special docker images to ensure compliance with the [manylinux rules]"
"(https://peps.python.org/pep-0599/#the-manylinux2014-policy). If you want to "
"publish linux wheels on pypi, **you need to use a manylinux docker image or "
"[build with zig](#use-zig)**."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:10
msgid ""
"The Rust compiler since version 1.64 [requires at least glibc 2.17](https://"
"blog.rust-lang.org/2022/08/01/Increasing-glibc-kernel-requirements.html), so "
"you need to use at least manylinux2014. For publishing, we recommend "
"enforcing the same manylinux version as the image with the manylinux flag, e."
"g. use `--manylinux 2014` if you are building in `quay.io/pypa/"
"manylinux2014_x86_64`. The [PyO3/maturin-action](https://github.com/PyO3/"
"maturin-action) github action already takes care of this if you set e.g. "
"`manylinux: 2014`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:14
msgid ""
"If you are publishing to PyPI, you can use `--compatibility pypi` to allow "
"only builds for targets that are accepted by PyPI, and reject builds for "
"unsupported operating systems and architectures."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:16
msgid ""
"maturin can check the generated library for manylinux compliance (an "
"auditwheel reimplementation) and gives the wheel the proper platform tag."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:18
msgid "If your system's glibc is too new, it will assign the `linux` tag."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:19
msgid ""
"If you link other shared libraries, maturin will try to bundle them within "
"the wheel, note that this requires [patchelf](https://github.com/NixOS/"
"patchelf), which can be installed along with maturin from PyPI: `pip install "
"maturin[patchelf]`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:22
msgid ""
"You can also manually disable those checks and directly use native linux "
"target with `--manylinux off`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:24
msgid ""
"The [pyo3/maturin](https://ghcr.io/pyo3/maturin) image is based on the "
"manylinux2014 image, and passes arguments to the `maturin` binary. You can "
"use it like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:30
msgid ""
"Note that this image is very basic and only contains python, maturin and "
"stable Rust. If you need additional tools, you can run commands inside the "
"manylinux container. See [konstin/complex-manylinux-maturin-docker](https://"
"github.com/konstin/complex-manylinux-maturin-docker) for a small educational "
"example or [nanoporetech/fast-ctc-decode](https://github.com/nanoporetech/"
"fast-ctc-decode/blob/b226ea0f2b2f4f474eff47349703d57d2ea4801b/.github/"
"workflows/publish.yml) for a real world setup."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:34
msgid ""
"```\n"
"Usage: maturin build [OPTIONS] [ARGS]...\n"
"\n"
"Arguments:\n"
"  [ARGS]...\n"
"          Rustc flags\n"
"\n"
"Options:\n"
"      --strip [<STRIP>]\n"
"          Strip the library for minimum file size. Can be set to `true` or "
"`false`, or used as a flag (`--strip` implies `true`)\n"
"\n"
"          [env: MATURIN_STRIP=]\n"
"          [possible values: true, false]\n"
"\n"
"      --sdist\n"
"          Build a source distribution and build wheels from it.\n"
"\n"
"          This verifies that the source distribution is complete and can be "
"used to build the project from source.\n"
"\n"
"      --pgo\n"
"          Build with Profile-Guided Optimization (PGO).\n"
"\n"
"          Requires `pgo-command` to be set in `[tool.maturin]` in pyproject."
"toml. This performs a three-phase build: instrumented build, profile "
"training, and optimized rebuild.\n"
"\n"
"  -i, --interpreter [<INTERPRETER>...]\n"
"          The python versions to build wheels for, given as the executables "
"of interpreters such as `python3.9` or `/usr/bin/python3.8`\n"
"\n"
"  -f, --find-interpreter\n"
"          Find interpreters from the host machine\n"
"\n"
"  -b, --bindings <BINDINGS>\n"
"          Which kind of bindings to use\n"
"\n"
"          [possible values: pyo3, pyo3-ffi, cffi, uniffi, bin]\n"
"\n"
"      --compatibility [<compatibility>...]\n"
"          Control the platform tag and PyPI compatibility.\n"
"\n"
"          This options offers both fine-grained control over the linux libc "
"tag and a more automatic PyPI-compatibility option.\n"
"\n"
"          The `pypi` option applies on all platforms and ensure that only "
"tags that can be uploaded to PyPI are used. The linux-specific options are "
"`manylinux` tags (for example `manylinux2014`/`manylinux_2_24`) or "
"`musllinux` tags (for example `musllinux_1_2`), and `linux` for the native "
"linux tag. They are\n"
"          ignored on non-linux platforms.\n"
"\n"
"          Note that `manylinux1` and `manylinux2010` are unsupported by the "
"rust compiler. Wheels with the native `linux` tag will be rejected by pypi, "
"unless they are separately validated by `auditwheel`.\n"
"\n"
"          The default is the lowest compatible `manylinux` tag, or plain "
"`linux` if nothing matched.\n"
"\n"
"      --auditwheel <AUDITWHEEL>\n"
"          Audit wheel for manylinux compliance\n"
"\n"
"          Possible values:\n"
"          - repair: Audit and repair wheel for manylinux compliance\n"
"          - check:  Check wheel for manylinux compliance, but do not repair\n"
"          - skip:   Don't check for manylinux compliance\n"
"\n"
"      --zig\n"
"          For manylinux targets, use zig to ensure compliance for the chosen "
"manylinux version\n"
"\n"
"          Default to manylinux2014/manylinux_2_17 if you do not specify an "
"`--compatibility`\n"
"\n"
"          Make sure you installed zig with `pip install maturin[zig]`\n"
"\n"
"  -o, --out <OUT>\n"
"          The directory to store the built wheels in. Defaults to a new "
"\"wheels\" directory in the project's target directory\n"
"\n"
"      --include-debuginfo\n"
"          Include debug info files (.pdb on Windows, .dSYM on macOS, .dwp on "
"Linux) in the wheel. When enabled, maturin automatically configures split-"
"debuginfo=packed so that separate debug info files are produced\n"
"\n"
"      --sbom-include <SBOM_INCLUDE>...\n"
"          Additional SBOM files to include in the `.dist-info/sboms` "
"directory. Can be specified multiple times\n"
"\n"
"  -q, --quiet\n"
"          Do not print cargo log messages\n"
"\n"
"      --ignore-rust-version\n"
"          Ignore `rust-version` specification in packages\n"
"\n"
"  -v, --verbose...\n"
"          Use verbose output (-vv very verbose/build.rs output)\n"
"\n"
"      --color <WHEN>\n"
"          Coloring: auto, always, never\n"
"\n"
"      --config <KEY=VALUE>\n"
"          Override a configuration value (unstable)\n"
"\n"
"  -Z <FLAG>\n"
"          Unstable (nightly-only) flags to Cargo, see 'cargo -Z help' for "
"details\n"
"\n"
"      --future-incompat-report\n"
"          Outputs a future incompatibility report at the end of the build "
"(unstable)\n"
"\n"
"      --compression-method <COMPRESSION_METHOD>\n"
"          Zip compression method. Only Stored and Deflated are currently "
"compatible with all package managers\n"
"\n"
"          Possible values:\n"
"          - deflated: Deflate compression (levels 0-9, default 6)\n"
"          - stored:   No compression\n"
"          - bzip2:    BZIP2 compression (levels 0-9, default 6)\n"
"          - zstd:     Zstandard compression (supported from Python 3.14; "
"levels -7-22, default 3)\n"
"\n"
"          [default: deflated]\n"
"\n"
"      --compression-level <COMPRESSION_LEVEL>\n"
"          Zip compression level. Defaults to method default\n"
"\n"
"      --compression-enable-large-file-support\n"
"          Whether to use large file support for ZIP files. Defaults to "
"false\n"
"\n"
"      --generate-stubs\n"
"          Auto generate Python type stubs by introspecting the binary. "
"Requires PyO3 and its \"experimental-inspect\" feature\n"
"\n"
"  -h, --help\n"
"          Print help (see a summary with '-h')\n"
"\n"
"Compilation Options:\n"
"  -r, --release\n"
"          Build artifacts in release mode, with optimizations\n"
"\n"
"  -j, --jobs <N>\n"
"          Number of parallel jobs, defaults to # of CPUs\n"
"\n"
"      --profile <PROFILE-NAME>\n"
"          Build artifacts with the specified Cargo profile\n"
"\n"
"      --target <TRIPLE>\n"
"          Build for the target triple\n"
"\n"
"          [env: CARGO_BUILD_TARGET=]\n"
"\n"
"      --target-dir <DIRECTORY>\n"
"          Directory for all generated artifacts\n"
"\n"
"      --timings=<FMTS>\n"
"          Timing output formats (unstable) (comma separated): html, json\n"
"\n"
"Feature Selection:\n"
"  -F, --features <FEATURES>\n"
"          Space or comma separated list of features to activate\n"
"\n"
"      --all-features\n"
"          Activate all available features\n"
"\n"
"      --no-default-features\n"
"          Do not activate the `default` feature\n"
"\n"
"Manifest Options:\n"
"  -m, --manifest-path <PATH>\n"
"          Path to Cargo.toml\n"
"\n"
"      --frozen\n"
"          Require Cargo.lock and cache are up to date\n"
"\n"
"      --locked\n"
"          Require Cargo.lock is up to date\n"
"\n"
"      --offline\n"
"          Run without accessing the network\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:194
msgid "Source Distribution"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:196
msgid ""
"Maturin supports building through `pyproject.toml`. To use it, create a "
"`pyproject.toml` next to your `Cargo.toml` with the following content:"
msgstr ""
"maturin 支援透過 `pyproject.toml` 進行建置。若要使用此功能，請在 `Cargo."
"toml` 旁建立一個內容如下的 `pyproject.toml`："

#: src/index.md:235
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=1.0,<2.0\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=1.0,<2.0\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"```"

#: src/distribution.md:204
msgid ""
"If a `pyproject.toml` with a `[build-system]` entry is present, maturin can "
"build a source distribution of your package when `--sdist` is specified. The "
"source distribution will contain the same files as `cargo package`. To only "
"build a source distribution, use the `maturin sdist` command."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:207
msgid ""
"You can then e.g. install your package with `pip install .`. With `pip "
"install . -v` you can see the output of cargo and maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:209
msgid ""
"You can use the options `compatibility`, `skip-auditwheel`, `bindings`, "
"`strip` and common Cargo build options such as `features` under `[tool."
"maturin]` the same way you would when running maturin directly. The "
"`bindings` key is required for cffi and bin projects as those can't be "
"automatically detected. Currently, all builds are in release mode (see [this "
"thread](https://discuss.python.org/t/pep-517-debug-vs-release-builds/1924) "
"for details)."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:212
msgid ""
"For a non-manylinux build with cffi bindings you could use the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:214
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=1.0,<2.0\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"bindings = \"cffi\"\n"
"compatibility = \"linux\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=1.0,<2.0\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"bindings = \"cffi\"\n"
"compatibility = \"linux\"\n"
"```"

#: src/distribution.md:224
msgid ""
"`manylinux` option is also accepted as an alias of `compatibility` for "
"backward compatibility with old version of maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:226
msgid ""
"To include arbitrary files in the sdist for use during compilation specify "
"`include` as an array of `path` globs with `format` set to `sdist`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:228
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"include = [{ path = \"path/**/*\", format = \"sdist\" }]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:235
msgid ""
"Maturin has decent cross compilation support for `pyo3` and `bin` bindings, "
"other kind of bindings may work but aren't tested regularly."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:238
msgid "Cross-compile to Linux/macOS"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:240
msgid "Use Docker"
msgstr "使用 Docker"

#: src/distribution.md:242
msgid ""
"For manylinux support the [manylinux-cross](https://github.com/rust-cross/"
"manylinux-cross) docker images can be used. And [maturin-action](https://"
"github.com/PyO3/maturin-action) makes it easy to do cross compilation on "
"GitHub Actions."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:245
msgid "Use Zig"
msgstr "使用 Zig"

#: src/distribution.md:247
msgid ""
"Since v0.12.7 maturin added support for linking with [`zig cc`](https://"
"andrewkelley.me/post/zig-cc-powerful-drop-in-replacement-gcc-clang.html), "
"compile for Linux works and is regularly tested on CI, other platforms may "
"also work but aren't tested regularly."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:250
msgid ""
"You can install zig following the [official documentation](https://ziglang."
"org/download), or install it from PyPI via `pip install ziglang`. Then pass "
"`--zig` to maturin `build` or `publish` commands to use it, for example"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:257
msgid "Cross-compile to Windows"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:259
msgid ""
"Pyo3 0.16.5 added an experimental feature `generate-import-lib` enables the "
"user to cross compile extension modules for Windows targets without setting "
"the `PYO3_CROSS_LIB_DIR` environment variable or providing any Windows "
"Python library files."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:263
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"pyo3 = { version = \"0.28.2\", features = [\"generate-import-lib\"] }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:268
msgid ""
"It uses an external [`python3-dll-a`](https://docs.rs/python3-dll-a/latest/"
"python3_dll_a/) crate to generate import libraries for the Python DLL for "
"MinGW-w64 and MSVC compile targets. Note: MSVC targets require LLVM binutils "
"or MSVC build tools to be available on the host system. More specifically, "
"`python3-dll-a` requires `llvm-dlltool` or `lib.exe` executable to be "
"present in `PATH` when targeting `*-pc-windows-msvc`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:273
msgid ""
"maturin integrates [`cargo-xwin`](https://github.com/messense/cargo-xwin) to "
"enable MSVC targets cross compilation support, it will download and unpack "
"the Microsoft CRT headers and import libraries, and Windows SDK headers and "
"import libraries needed for compiling and linking automatically."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:277
msgid ""
"**By using this to cross compiling to Windows MSVC targets you are consented "
"to accept the license at [https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2086102]"
"(https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2086102)**. (Building on Windows "
"natively does not apply.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:280
msgid "GitHub Actions"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:282
msgid ""
"If your project uses GitHub Actions, you can use the `maturin generate-ci` "
"command to generate a GitHub Actions workflow file."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:289
msgid "There are some options to customize the generated workflow file:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:291
msgid ""
"```\n"
"Generate CI configuration\n"
"\n"
"Usage: maturin generate-ci [OPTIONS] <CI>\n"
"\n"
"Arguments:\n"
"  <CI>\n"
"          CI provider\n"
"\n"
"          Possible values:\n"
"          - github: GitHub\n"
"\n"
"Options:\n"
"  -m, --manifest-path <PATH>\n"
"          Path to Cargo.toml\n"
"\n"
"  -v, --verbose...\n"
"          Use verbose output.\n"
"\n"
"          * Default: Show build information and `cargo build` output. * `-"
"v`: Use `cargo build -v`.\n"
"          * `-vv`: Show debug logging and use `cargo build -vv`. * `-vvv`: "
"Show trace logging.\n"
"\n"
"          You can configure fine-grained logging using the `RUST_LOG` "
"environment variable.\n"
"          (<https://docs.rs/tracing-subscriber/latest/tracing_subscriber/"
"filter/struct.EnvFilter.html#directives>)\n"
"\n"
"  -o, --output <PATH>\n"
"          Output path\n"
"\n"
"          [default: -]\n"
"\n"
"      --platform <platform>...\n"
"          Platform support\n"
"\n"
"          [default: linux musllinux windows macos]\n"
"\n"
"          Possible values:\n"
"          - all:        All\n"
"          - manylinux:  Manylinux\n"
"          - musllinux:  Musllinux\n"
"          - windows:    Windows\n"
"          - macos:      macOS\n"
"          - emscripten: Emscripten\n"
"\n"
"      --pytest\n"
"          Enable pytest\n"
"\n"
"      --zig\n"
"          Use zig to do cross compilation\n"
"\n"
"      --skip-attestation\n"
"          Skip artifact attestation\n"
"\n"
"  -h, --help\n"
"          Print help (see a summary with '-h')\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:347
msgid "Using PyPI's trusted publishing"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:349
msgid ""
"By default, the workflow provided by `generate-ci` will publish the release "
"artifacts to PyPI using API token authentication. However, maturin also "
"supports [trusted publishing (OpenID Connect)](https://docs.pypi.org/trusted-"
"publishers/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:351
msgid ""
"To enable it, modify the `release` action in the generated GitHub workflow "
"file:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:353
msgid ""
"remove `MATURIN_PYPI_TOKEN` from the `env` section to make maturin use "
"trusted publishing"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:354
msgid ""
"add `id-token: write` to the action's `permissions` (see [Configuring OpenID "
"Connect in PyPI](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/deployment/security-"
"hardening-your-deployments/configuring-openid-connect-in-pypi) from GitHub's "
"documentation)."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:355
msgid "if `Environment name: pypi` was set in PyPI, add `environment: pypi`"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:357
msgid ""
"Make sure to follow the steps listed in [PyPI's documentation](https://docs."
"pypi.org/trusted-publishers/adding-a-publisher/) to set up your GitHub "
"repository as a trusted publisher in the PyPI project settings before "
"attempting to run the workflow."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:1
msgid "Environment Variables"
msgstr "環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:3
msgid ""
"Maturin reads a number of environment variables which you can use to "
"configure the build process. Here is a list of all environment variables "
"that are read by maturin:"
msgstr ""
"Maturin 會讀取多個環境變數，您可以用來組態建置過程。以下是 maturin 會讀取的所"
"有環境變數列表："

#: src/environment-variables.md:6
msgid "Cargo environment variables"
msgstr "Cargo 環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:8
msgid ""
"See [environment variables Cargo reads](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/"
"reference/environment-variables.html#environment-variables-cargo-reads)"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:10
msgid "Python environment variables"
msgstr "Python 環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:12
msgid "`VIRTUAL_ENV`: Path to a Python virtual environment"
msgstr "`VIRTUAL_ENV`：Python 虛擬環境的路徑"

#: src/environment-variables.md:13
msgid "`CONDA_PREFIX`: Path to a conda environment"
msgstr "`CONDA_PREFIX`：Conda 環境的路徑"

#: src/environment-variables.md:14
msgid "`_PYTHON_SYSCONFIGDATA_NAME`: Name of a `sysconfigdata*.py` file"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:15
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_PEP517_USE_BASE_PYTHON`: Use base Python executable instead of venv "
"Python executable in PEP 517 build to avoid unnecessary rebuilds, should not "
"be set when the sdist build requires packages installed in venv."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:17
msgid "PEP 517 build environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:19
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_PEP517_ARGS`: Extra arguments passed to `maturin` during PEP 517 "
"builds (e.g. `pip install .`). The value is parsed using shell-style "
"splitting. For example: `MATURIN_PEP517_ARGS=\"--features foo --profile "
"release\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:20
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_NO_INSTALL_RUST`: If set, do not attempt to auto-install Rust via "
"`puccinialin` when `cargo` is not found during PEP 517 builds."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:22
msgid "pip config-settings"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:24
msgid ""
"You can also pass extra maturin arguments via pip's `--config-settings` flag:"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:27
msgid "\"build-args=--features foo\""
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:27
msgid "# or with the namespaced key\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:29
msgid "\"maturin.build-args=--features foo\""
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:32
msgid ""
"Config-settings take priority over `MATURIN_PEP517_ARGS`; the environment "
"variable is only used when no `build-args` config-setting is provided."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:34
msgid "Upload environment variables"
msgstr "上傳環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:36
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_PYPI_TOKEN`: PyPI token for uploading wheels (token-based "
"authentication)"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:37
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_REPOSITORY`: The repository (package index) to upload the package "
"to, defaults to `pypi`"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:38
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_REPOSITORY_URL`: The URL of the registry where the wheels are "
"uploaded to, overrides `MATURIN_REPOSITORY`"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:39
msgid "`MATURIN_USERNAME`: Username for pypi or your custom registry"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:40
msgid "`MATURIN_PASSWORD`: Password for pypi or your custom registry"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:41
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_NON_INTERACTIVE`: Do not interactively prompt for username/password "
"if the required credentials are missing"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:43
msgid "`pyo3` environment variables"
msgstr "`pyo3` 環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:45
msgid ""
"`PYO3_CROSS_PYTHON_VERSION`: Python version to use for cross compilation"
msgstr "`PYO3_CROSS_PYTHON_VERSION`：用於交叉編譯的 Python 版本"

#: src/environment-variables.md:46
msgid ""
"`PYO3_CROSS_LIB_DIR`: This variable can be set to the directory containing "
"the target's libpython DSO and the associated `_sysconfigdata*.py` file for "
"Unix-like targets, or the Python DLL import libraries for the Windows target."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:47
msgid ""
"`PYO3_CONFIG_FILE`: Path to a [pyo3 config file](https://pyo3.rs/latest/"
"building-and-distribution.html#advanced-config-files)"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:49
msgid "Networking environment variables"
msgstr "網路環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:51
msgid "`HTTP_PROXY` / `HTTPS_PROXY`: Proxy to use for HTTP/HTTPS requests"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:52
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_CA_BUNDLE` / `REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE` / `CURL_CA_BUNDLE`: Path to a CA "
"bundle to use for HTTPS requests"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:54
msgid "Other environment variables"
msgstr "其他環境變數"

#: src/environment-variables.md:56
msgid "`MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET`: The minimum macOS version to target"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:57
msgid "`IPHONEOS_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET`: The minimum iOS version to target"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:58
msgid ""
"`SOURCE_DATE_EPOCH`: The time to use for the timestamp in the wheel metadata"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:59
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_EMSCRIPTEN_VERSION`: The version of emscripten to use for "
"emscripten builds"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:60
msgid "`MATURIN_STRIP`: Strip the library for minimum file size"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:61
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_NO_MISSING_BUILD_BACKEND_WARNING`: Suppress missing build backend "
"warning"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:62
msgid ""
"`MATURIN_USE_XWIN`: Set to `1` to force to use `xwin` for cross compiling "
"even on Windows that supports native compilation"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:63
msgid ""
"`ANDROID_API_LEVEL`: The Android API level to target when cross compiling "
"for Android"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:64
msgid ""
"`TARGET_SYSROOT`: The sysroot to use for auditwheel wheel when cross "
"compiling"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:65
msgid ""
"`ARCHFLAGS`: Flags to control the architecture of the build on macOS, for "
"example you can use `ARCHFLAGS=\"-arch x86_64 -arch arm64\"` to build "
"universal2 wheels"
msgstr ""

